  "content": {
    "home": {
      "title": "HTML Tutorial",
      "paragraphs": [
        "HTML is the standard markup language for Web pages.",
        "HTML is easy to learn."
      ]
    },
    "introduction": {
      "title": "HTML Introduction",
      "paragraphs": [
        "HTML stands for Hyper Text Markup Language.",
        "HTML describes the structure of a Web page."
      ]
    },
    "elements": {
      "title": "HTML Elements",
      "sections": [
        {
          "heading": "What is an HTML Element?",
          "paragraphs": [
            "An HTML element is defined by a start tag, some content, and an end tag.",
            "The HTML element is everything from the start tag to the end tag."
          ],
          "example": "<tagname>Content goes here...</tagname>"
        },
        {
          "heading": "Examples of HTML Elements",
          "examples": [
            "<h1>My First Heading</h1>",
            "<p>My first paragraph.</p>"
          ],
          "table": {
            "headers": ["Start tag", "Element content", "End tag"],
            "rows": [
              ["<h1>", "My First Heading", "</h1>"],
              ["<p>", "My first paragraph.", "</p>"],
              ["<br>", "none", "none"]
            ]
          },
          "note": "Some HTML elements have no content (like the <br> element). These are called empty elements and they do not have an end tag."
        },
        {
          "heading": "Nested HTML Elements",
          "paragraphs": [
            "HTML elements can be nested, meaning elements can contain other elements.",
            "All HTML documents consist of nested HTML elements."
          ],
          "code": "<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n<body>\n\n<h1>My First Heading</h1>\n<p>My first paragraph.</p>\n\n</body>\n</html>"
        },
        {
          "heading": "Example Explained",
          "paragraphs": [
            "The <html> element is the root element that defines the whole HTML document.",
            "Inside the <html> element is the <body> element, which defines the document's body.",
            "Inside the <body> element are other elements such as <h1> and <p>."
          ],
          "examples": [
            "<html>...</html>",
            "<body>...</body>",
            "<h1>My First Heading</h1>",
            "<p>My first paragraph.</p>"
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "Never Skip the End Tag",
          "paragraphs": [
            "Some HTML elements may display correctly even if you forget the end tag.",
            "However, you should never rely on this because it can cause unexpected results or errors."
          ],
          "code": "<html>\n<body>\n\n<p>This is a paragraph\n<p>This is a paragraph\n\n</body>\n</html>"
        },
        {
          "heading": "Empty HTML Elements",
          "paragraphs": [
            "HTML elements with no content are called empty elements.",
            "The <br> tag defines a line break and is an empty element without a closing tag."
          ],
          "example": "<p>This is a <br> paragraph with a line break.</p>"
        },
        {
          "heading": "HTML is Not Case Sensitive",
          "paragraphs": [
            "HTML tags are not case sensitive: <P> means the same as <p>.",
            "The HTML standard does not require lowercase tags, but W3C recommends lowercase and requires it for XHTML.",
            "In this tutorial, lowercase tag names are used."
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "Exercise",
          "exercise": {
            "question": "True or False: Empty elements must have a closing tag.",
            "options": ["True", "False"],
            "answer": "False"
          }
        },
        {
          "heading": "HTML Tag Reference",
          "paragraphs": [
            "HTML tag references provide additional information about tags and their attributes."
          ],
          "table": {
            "headers": ["Tag", "Description"],
            "rows": [
              ["<html>", "Defines the root of an HTML document"],
              ["<body>", "Defines the document's body"],
              ["<h1> to <h6>", "Defines HTML headings"]
            ]
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    "attributes": {
      "title": "HTML Attributes",
      "sections": [
        {
          "heading": "HTML Attributes",
          "paragraphs": [
            "HTML attributes provide additional information about HTML elements.",
            "All HTML elements can have attributes.",
            "Attributes are always specified in the start tag.",
            "Attributes usually come in name/value pairs like: name=\"value\"."
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "The href Attribute",
          "paragraphs": [
            "The <a> tag defines a hyperlink. The href attribute specifies the URL of the page the link goes to."
          ],
          "examples": [
            "<a href=\"https://www.w3schools.com\">Visit W3Schools</a>"
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "The src Attribute",
          "paragraphs": [
            "The <img> tag is used to embed an image in an HTML page.",
            "The src attribute specifies the path to the image to be displayed."
          ],
          "examples": [
            "<img src=\"img_girl.jpg\">",
            "<img src=\"img_girl.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"600\">"
          ],
          "note": "It is almost always best to use relative URLs."
        },
        {
          "heading": "The alt Attribute",
          "paragraphs": [
            "The alt attribute specifies alternate text for an image if it cannot be displayed."
          ],
          "examples": ["<img src=\"img_girl.jpg\" alt=\"Girl with a jacket\">"]
        },
        {
          "heading": "Chapter Summary",
          "paragraphs": [
            "All HTML elements can have attributes.",
            "The href attribute specifies the URL of a link.",
            "The src attribute specifies the image path.",
            "The alt attribute provides alternate text."
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "Exercise",
          "exercise": {
            "question": "Which of the following is a correct syntax for using an HTML attribute?",
            "options": [
              "<img src='img_girl.jpg'>",
              "<img src('img_girl.jpg')>",
              "<img src:'img_girl.jpg'>"
            ],
            "answer": "<img src='img_girl.jpg'>"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}
